<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-06-28T08:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-06-28T08:00:00-05:00" n="63" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d63">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4 Steering Committee/482:
                                Telegram</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi>
                                    (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-06-28T14:00:00+01:00">June
                                        28, 1935—2 p.m.</date>
                                    <lb/> [Received June 28—10:20 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>294. From Hugh Wilson. Henderson has confirmed to me approximately
                                what I reported recently from Geneva after conversation with
                                Aghnides. He contemplates calling a Bureau meeting for September
                                16th probably followed by a General Commission meeting 10 days
                                later.</p>
                            <p>Henderson explained that the negotiations appeared to be taking a
                                turn which for good or evil is not in accordance with Conference
                                procedure. He can no longer assume the responsibility of allowing
                                the Conference to lapse through inanition. He feels he must share
                                that responsibility with the Bureau. Unless at the Bureau meeting
                                there are indications of a speedy resumption of work Henderson will
                                urge the Bureau to adopt a resolution to lay before the General
                                Commission the question of the future of the Conference.</p>
                            <p>Am writing Mr. Davis direct.</p>
                            <p>Cipher text to Geneva. [Wilson.]</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                                </signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>